WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.472
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.960 --> 00:00:08.270
SPEAKER: Welcome, Anthony
Myint and Karen Leibowitz,

00:00:08.270 --> 00:00:11.660
who are husband and wife
co-founders of the Perennial.

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:14.450
This is an award-winning San
Francisco restaurant and bar

00:00:14.450 --> 00:00:17.000
dedicated to making
food the delicious

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:18.890
solution to climate change.

00:00:18.890 --> 00:00:21.905
And when I say
award-winning, I mean Best

00:00:21.905 --> 00:00:25.430
New Restaurants in America,
25 Most Daring Companies

00:00:25.430 --> 00:00:27.290
in America, Best
Bars in America,

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:31.364
Best Cocktails in
Francisco, Most Sustainable.

00:00:31.364 --> 00:00:33.780
And they've been awarded from
places like Bon Apetit, Food

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:36.830
and Wine, San Francisco
Magazine, 20 Most Important

00:00:36.830 --> 00:00:40.790
Restaurants in America,
and a Michelin Star.

00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:41.990
Pretty big deal.

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:44.780
So let me tell you a
little bit more about them.

00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:47.750
Anthony and Karen coauthored
the memoir cookbook

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:50.930
Mission Street Food, Recipes
and Ideas from an Improbable

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:53.180
Restaurant back in 2011.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:54.530
They often work together, though

00:00:54.530 --> 00:00:56.450
Anthony is primarily
a restaurateur

00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:59.660
whose projects include Mission
Chinese Food, Commonwealth,

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:00.950
and Mission Cantina.

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:03.020
And Karen is primarily
a food writer

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:05.390
who has written for Lucky
Peach, Food and Wine,

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:08.210
and The New York Times
among other publications.

00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:10.550
She's also, though, co-author
with Dominique Crenn

00:01:10.550 --> 00:01:12.890
of Autelier Crenn of
"Metamorphosis of Taste."

00:01:12.890 --> 00:01:14.390
She's the Director
of Communications

00:01:14.390 --> 00:01:16.014
for the Perennial,
and although Anthony

00:01:16.014 --> 00:01:17.619
doesn't have an
official title, he's

00:01:17.619 --> 00:01:19.910
responsible for dreaming up
all the weird environmental

00:01:19.910 --> 00:01:20.600
projects.

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:23.040
I'm going to let
them get started.

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:24.292
Welcome.

00:01:24.292 --> 00:01:27.268
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:30.970
KAREN LEIBOWITZ:
Well, thanks so much.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.750
Thanks for having us.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:35.200
I am Karen Leibowitz.

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:36.400
This is Anthony Myint.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:38.590
The other title we've
come up with for him

00:01:38.590 --> 00:01:42.930
is Problem Solver,
Problem Creator.

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:49.000
So the Perennial is unusual in
the restaurant world in that

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.280
it's very mission-driven.

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:55.060
We see it as an opportunity
to engage people

00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:57.790
in the idea of
transforming the food

00:01:57.790 --> 00:02:01.750
system through a kind
of environmentalism

00:02:01.750 --> 00:02:03.410
without compromise.

00:02:06.710 --> 00:02:09.949
So here are some pictures
of the Perennial.

00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:13.360
The bread, which actually
we brought for you today,

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:15.610
which is made from
a perennial grain.

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:18.980
So we'll talk more about
why that's important,

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:22.690
but basically it's part of our
larger project of combating

00:02:22.690 --> 00:02:25.260
climate change through food.

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:29.380
There's our bar, and
cocktails, and beef tartar.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:32.620
And we'll talk about
why meat is actually not

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:36.585
off the menu at the Perennial.

00:02:36.585 --> 00:02:37.960
ANTHONY MYINT: So
I think quickly

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:40.942
we'll just do a background.

00:02:40.942 --> 00:02:42.400
Thanks for the
introduction, Julia.

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:48.460
And just to clarify one thing,
because sometimes restaurants

00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:51.130
are touchy about
accolades and things--

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:53.290
so we helped open a restaurant
called Commonwealth,

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:56.500
and Commonwealth
has a Michelin Star.

00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:00.770
So not the Perennial,
though we're hoping someday.

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:04.870
So we have somewhat
humble origins

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:08.200
in the restaurant industry,
which as Julia mentioned

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:11.870
are kind of documented in
this book Mission Street Food.

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:17.350
And so it was in 2008 when we
basically kind of got started,

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:20.920
and if you think
back to that time,

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:24.460
there were not really
gourmet food trucks or pop-up

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:25.750
restaurants.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:27.970
It was the recession
and people were

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:32.200
looking for interesting dining
experience kind of on a budget.

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:35.050
And Twitter had just
opened, or started,

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:37.810
but we didn't really use
Twitter or understand

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:39.490
any of that stuff.

00:03:39.490 --> 00:03:46.010
And we sublet a Guatemalan
snack cart on a Thursday night,

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:50.230
and then basically tried to
serve gourmet tacos from it.

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.660
And we never really thought
that that would be successful.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:57.610
We just were doing
it kind of for fun.

00:03:57.610 --> 00:04:02.779
The internet being as such,
things kind of snowballed

00:04:02.779 --> 00:04:04.570
and a friend of ours
wrote a blog about it,

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:06.950
and then a local
food press eater

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:09.280
dot com wrote a story about it.

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:15.670
I think the headline called
me a high-falutin line cook.

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:19.042
And so I was standing on
the street corner waiting

00:04:19.042 --> 00:04:20.500
for the truck to
show up, and I had

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:23.010
a cooler with a bunch of mise
en place and different stuff,

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:24.370
and there was another guy
standing on the corner

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:25.630
also looking at his phone.

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:28.090
And I asked him, hey, are
you here for something?

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:30.820
And he said, yeah, I'm
here for the food truck.

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:33.550
And so we had people
waiting for the truck

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:36.940
before I had even set foot in
the truck for the first time.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:38.590
And then Karen was rushing back.

00:04:38.590 --> 00:04:41.440
She was a grad student
in Berkeley at the time,

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.780
and ran back, and we
were scrambling around

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:46.249
and didn't really know
what we were doing.

00:04:46.249 --> 00:04:48.290
And so we did that for a
few weeks and then moved

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:53.140
into basically a crappy
hole-in-the-wall Chinese

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.860
restaurant, which is now the
home of Mission Chinese Food.

00:04:56.860 --> 00:05:01.660
And we did pop-up events
once a week at first,

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:03.230
and then eventually
twice a week.

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:05.620
And we invited guest
chefs and line cooks

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:07.870
from around the city to
come do half the menu,

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:09.280
and we did the other half.

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:10.990
And again, we never
really expected

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:14.960
it to last for very long
or be leading to anything.

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:17.700
And so we gave all the
profits away to charity,

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:22.240
and that was a fun way
to be part of a bigger

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:24.290
San Francisco community.

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:30.400
And so eventually, we kind
of decided, why are we

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:33.940
making things really hard and
serving Mexi-Chinian food one

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:35.860
night, and a whole-hog
dinner, and using

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:39.910
the wok with charcoal in it,
and grilling octopus and stuff.

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:42.010
Why don't we just
use the woks as woks?

00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:45.900
And so we worked with
someone who was a guest chef,

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:49.330
a Korean adoptee
from Oklahoma named

00:05:49.330 --> 00:05:55.739
Danny Bowen, who at the time
I think was a line cook.

00:05:55.739 --> 00:05:57.280
KAREN LEIBOWITZ:
Only wearing shorts.

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:00.310
ANTHONY MYINT: Swim
trunks, I think, every day.

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.500
And so we started
Mission Chinese,

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:05.740
and we decided at some point--

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:07.480
or went from the
get-go with that one.

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.700
Let's not rotate the
charities all the time.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:14.680
Let's just give $0.75 from
each entree to the food bank.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:19.870
It was a kind of
random-seeming project

00:06:19.870 --> 00:06:22.480
that, again, I don't think
that we necessarily thought,

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.250
we'll been doing this forever.

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:27.050
And then eventually it
became really successful.

00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:29.480
Danny moved to New York
and also opened there.

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:31.640
When he opened in New
York, the restaurant

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:34.160
won New York Times Restaurant
of the Year in 2012,

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:40.790
despite being located inside
of a Thai takeout counter.

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:44.017
And since then, we've
raised over a million meals

00:06:44.017 --> 00:06:45.350
for the San Francisco food bank.

00:06:45.350 --> 00:06:47.510
And so I think this
speaks towards kind

00:06:47.510 --> 00:06:49.310
of the possibilities
in the restaurant

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:55.834
industry of finding a project
that resonates with the public.

00:06:55.834 --> 00:06:56.750
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah.

00:06:56.750 --> 00:07:00.390
So the same summer that we
opened Mission Chinese Food--

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:05.092
2010-- we also worked with some
former coworkers of Anthony's

00:07:05.092 --> 00:07:06.800
to open a restaurant
called Commonwealth,

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:09.500
which was more of the
fine-dining version of this.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:11.540
But I think in
both cases, we were

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.810
interested in seeing how
food and restaurants can

00:07:14.810 --> 00:07:17.770
be used to convey meaning.

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:22.400
So we were creating a kind
of link with the food bank,

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:26.130
and asking people to think
more about food broadly.

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:28.370
Not just why it was
delicious, though it

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:32.240
should be delicious, but also
sort of what food means to us.

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:36.110
And as a way to
make connections.

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:40.520
So from there, we wrote the
book, Mission Street Food,

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:47.480
and talked about that journey,
and even gave a Google Talk.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:53.330
And then in 2012 we had
a baby, who is now a kid.

00:07:53.330 --> 00:07:57.530
But I feel like that
really focused us

00:07:57.530 --> 00:08:00.200
on issues of the future, and
thinking about especially

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:04.040
climate change, and we
were dismayed to learn

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:07.520
that by some accounts
the food system is

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:12.750
responsible for up to
50% of the greenhouse gas

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:13.770
emissions in the world.

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:15.640
And as people
working with food, we

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:17.800
felt like, what
can we do better?

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:21.210
And so we started trying to
improve operations at Mission

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:22.380
Chinese and Commonwealth.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:26.340
But we started to think, what
would happen if you really

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:30.830
started a restaurant with the
idea of climate change in mind?

00:08:30.830 --> 00:08:33.576
And that's where
the Perennial began.

00:08:33.576 --> 00:08:34.409
ANTHONY MYINT: Yeah.

00:08:34.409 --> 00:08:39.000
So as Karen mentioned, I feel
like as we were researching,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.710
it just seemed
completely undeniable

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:44.290
that food is a really big
part of climate change.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:49.320
And I think something that we
realized also along the way

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:52.980
is that the restaurant
sector is almost as

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:56.169
big as the entire
agriculture sector.

00:08:56.169 --> 00:08:57.960
And there was a lot of
potential to, again,

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:02.070
use the restaurant sector to
try to change the food system.

00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:04.060
You can kind of see
on this line graph--

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:06.780
or first, I should
say we don't get

00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:09.270
into any of this kind of
stuff at the Perennial.

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:15.670
This is just for
this kind of talk.

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:17.630
So there's a line
chart here that

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:19.647
shows atmospheric
greenhouse gases,

00:09:19.647 --> 00:09:21.980
and of course there's other
things-- industrialisation--

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:22.820
going on.

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:25.790
You can see really
big inflection points

00:09:25.790 --> 00:09:27.320
around the invention
of the plough

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:32.750
and the advent of
chemical fertilizer.

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:36.320
This is an image
from the Dust Bowl.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.310
I think, even as
food professionals,

00:09:39.310 --> 00:09:42.820
we really several
years ago could not

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:45.220
have told you what
constitutes good farming.

00:09:45.220 --> 00:09:47.680
We understood
organic and local--

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:49.570
these are important things--

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:52.330
but I don't think we
actually understand farming.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:55.660
And I think that
kind of makes sense.

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:58.090
A lot of us have grown
up in a generation

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:02.590
of industrial agriculture and
pretty disconnected from food.

00:10:02.590 --> 00:10:05.260
In this era, there
was also fake news.

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:07.930
I guess that's sort of
pertinent these days.

00:10:07.930 --> 00:10:11.110
And the railroad
companies had a pitch

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:13.780
like, the ploughs
follow the rain.

00:10:13.780 --> 00:10:17.770
And people rushed out
west to claim land,

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:20.230
dug up perennial
grasses that used

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:25.372
to live in these ecosystems,
and then started crop farming.

00:10:25.372 --> 00:10:27.720
They eventually realized
you can't do that.

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:29.400
The environment is too dry.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:31.500
If there's no rain six
months of the year,

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:33.120
this doesn't make sense.

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:36.300
This led to what is
called the Dust Bowl.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:40.110
Dust from Oklahoma is flying
through the air and landing

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:41.700
in Washington, D.C.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:43.170
And it kind of
had to go that far

00:10:43.170 --> 00:10:50.040
before the government created
an agency to work on soil.

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:52.662
So on the one hand,
that is pretty negative,

00:10:52.662 --> 00:10:54.870
but on the other hand it
speaks towards the potential

00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:57.660
to radically change
the whole food system

00:10:57.660 --> 00:10:59.880
and farming really
quickly in response

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:01.860
to that kind of problem.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.660
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: So again,
this is not actually

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:08.730
what we talk about at
the Perennial at all

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:13.560
because we got into the project
with a kind of, I think,

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:17.265
normal standard orientation
to environmentalism

00:11:17.265 --> 00:11:19.140
that it's all
about conservation,

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:20.520
or doing less bad.

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:23.040
But as we got into it what
we discovered was actually,

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:27.120
agriculture has the
capacity to really repair

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:32.040
the damage of climate
change because plants

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:37.180
draw down CO2 and can
store carbon in the soil.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:39.810
And so we started to really
think about the power,

00:11:39.810 --> 00:11:43.490
especially of perennial
plants, to restore the soil

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:46.060
and reverse climate change.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:49.050
And so we were really
excited because it

00:11:49.050 --> 00:11:51.690
felt like we had this
optimistic message,

00:11:51.690 --> 00:11:56.520
and it's not just do less,
like eat less, do whatever,

00:11:56.520 --> 00:12:02.070
but really a message
of positive action.

00:12:02.070 --> 00:12:05.670
So that was exciting for us,
and through that research

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:09.630
we discovered that there
are all these new efforts

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:14.620
to make perennials really part
of the climate change solution.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:19.200
So here's an example
of a plant that's

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:26.370
just recently been released and
approved for human consumption.

00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:27.990
It's called Kernza.

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:30.540
It was developed by the
Land Institute in Kansas,

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:33.000
and you can see on
the top there is wheat

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:34.950
and on the bottom
there is Kernza.

00:12:34.950 --> 00:12:38.100
And Anthony can't even reach
all the way to the end of it.

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:38.988
This is--

00:12:38.988 --> 00:12:41.029
AUDIENCE: Can you bring
it a little more forward?

00:12:41.029 --> 00:12:43.760
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: I think
a little more down, too.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:50.100
So you can see that the roots
are not only longer, but also

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:52.230
thicker and more complex.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:57.650
And they become the environment
for all sorts of life--

00:12:57.650 --> 00:13:00.960
and microorganisms
and worms that

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:05.580
also are working on making the
soil more of a carbon sink.

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:10.989
So that's the grain that
we're using in the bread

00:13:10.989 --> 00:13:11.780
that you're eating.

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:12.855
Let's just drop it.

00:13:12.855 --> 00:13:13.605
ANTHONY MYINT: OK.

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:19.320
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: And that has
been an exciting thing for us.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:24.180
We're the first restaurant to
be making our bread from Kernza.

00:13:24.180 --> 00:13:27.020
It's not 100%
Kernza-- it's a mix--

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:28.861
but it--

00:13:28.861 --> 00:13:30.360
ANTHONY MYINT: So
the Land Institute

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:34.020
has been naturally breeding
this grain for the last 15 years

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:36.660
in conjunction with the
University of Minnesota,

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:40.680
and it represents basically a
radical shift in agriculture

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:43.950
back to perennial polycultures.

00:13:43.950 --> 00:13:46.530
And so, again, with the
Dust Bowl and stuff,

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:50.760
the prairies used to be covered
with plants like Kernza--

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:53.790
perennial grasses that
evolved in that ecosystem.

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:56.160
We plowed it up to
plants like wheat,

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:58.280
which you can see
on the poster, just

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:01.050
have much smaller root systems.

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:03.960
All the root systems
represent themselves--

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:06.030
you know, carbon in
the atmosphere that

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:07.500
can be back in the soil.

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:12.960
And as Karen mentioned, also a
whole ecosystem of microbiology

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.900
called the resosphere
that surrounds the roots.

00:14:15.900 --> 00:14:19.890
And so the Land Institute
embarked on this journey

00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:22.470
to basically take
agriculture back

00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:28.620
to that kind of working
with natural systems,

00:14:28.620 --> 00:14:30.720
instead of working
with fertilizer

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:33.000
and extracting from the soil.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.290
And so Kernza is a hybrid
between perennial wheat grass

00:14:37.290 --> 00:14:41.190
and wheat, and it's basically
in version 1.0. now.

00:14:41.190 --> 00:14:45.210
So you can get it at
the Perennial as bread.

00:14:45.210 --> 00:14:47.800
It's also available
commercially on the West Coast

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:52.320
at Whole Foods as beer
called Long Route Ale.

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:56.610
And that was pioneered by the
company Patagonia in their food

00:14:56.610 --> 00:14:58.500
line Patagonia Provisions.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:00.660
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: You can
see there's meat there.

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:04.560
I think that there is a
kind of prevailing belief

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:06.750
that meat is the
worst thing that you

00:15:06.750 --> 00:15:07.926
can do for the environment.

00:15:07.926 --> 00:15:09.300
One of the things
that we learned

00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:12.960
is there are ways of
managing animals that

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:17.430
promote perennial
grasses and can actually

00:15:17.430 --> 00:15:19.050
be climate beneficial.

00:15:19.050 --> 00:15:22.920
So I'm going to show
you a little video.

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:24.270
It's very short.

00:15:24.270 --> 00:15:28.738
We made this for an event
at the Asian Art Museum.

00:16:56.960 --> 00:16:58.520
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: So
at the Perennial,

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:01.940
we've been serving
meat from a ranch that

00:17:01.940 --> 00:17:04.970
follows this protocol.

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:06.800
It's called Stemple Creek.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.670
And we've also been purchasing
the animal in large cuts

00:17:10.670 --> 00:17:15.109
so that we find a place
for all the parts.

00:17:15.109 --> 00:17:18.200
And so we have a
dining room and a bar,

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:22.069
and we can have
different kinds of cuts

00:17:22.069 --> 00:17:23.930
for different applications.

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:26.359
And also trying to
think about meat

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:29.810
as not the centerpiece
of the meal.

00:17:29.810 --> 00:17:32.700
So all of those together.

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:35.540
And I think one of the
things is that putting

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:38.570
such a focus on soil,
and the capacity for soil

00:17:38.570 --> 00:17:45.110
to be a carbon sink, means that
we also are recognizing that it

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:47.510
doesn't make sense
to, for example,

00:17:47.510 --> 00:17:51.380
grow herbs in soil, which are
never going to really rebuild

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:51.900
the soil.

00:17:51.900 --> 00:17:54.590
So we have another
project where we're

00:17:54.590 --> 00:18:00.250
taking food waste from the
Perennial and using it to power

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:04.010
a greenhouse, which is just
right across the bridge

00:18:04.010 --> 00:18:08.090
in Oakland and kind of
frees up land for more

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:10.220
perennial kinds of crops.

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:12.230
But just to walk
you through it--

00:18:12.230 --> 00:18:15.270
and I should mention that
the illustration on the left

00:18:15.270 --> 00:18:20.190
was by the local artist
Wendy McNaughton,

00:18:20.190 --> 00:18:23.680
and the one on the right
is by John Adams who also

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:26.540
who worked with
us on that video.

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:28.190
So we take the food scraps--

00:18:28.190 --> 00:18:31.670
I mean, even if you're really
conscientious about food waste,

00:18:31.670 --> 00:18:36.050
there's still certain
things like onion peels,

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:40.280
and that goes to
our worm bin, worms

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:43.670
are fed to fish, the fish
fertilize water, which

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:46.790
is used partly to
irrigate our raised beds,

00:18:46.790 --> 00:18:51.870
but also in a system,
which is like hydroponics

00:18:51.870 --> 00:18:56.300
but instead of using chemical
fertilizer the nutrition is

00:18:56.300 --> 00:19:00.470
coming from
essentially fish poop.

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:04.730
And then so we can grow kind of
specialty herbs and lettuces,

00:19:04.730 --> 00:19:07.130
which are then served
at the Perennial.

00:19:07.130 --> 00:19:08.630
ANTHONY MYINT: One
thing that really

00:19:08.630 --> 00:19:11.150
got us excited
about aquaponics was

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:13.610
learning about a
facility in Minneapolis

00:19:13.610 --> 00:19:16.500
that is in the former
Hamm's Brewing Company.

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:18.200
And so it's a
six-level facility,

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:19.730
and they're producing
on one level

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:22.260
kind of using all the
plumbing from the brewery that

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:24.710
was preexisting and
they're doing aquaponics.

00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:27.980
And as demand for the
products increase,

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:30.190
they project that they
will be able to produce

00:19:30.190 --> 00:19:33.830
700,000 pounds of lettuce
and 150,000 pounds of fish

00:19:33.830 --> 00:19:34.940
per year.

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:38.510
So that completely
blew my mind, and I

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:42.530
think that we also
read some stats where

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:44.360
at the end of World
War II, something

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.550
like 40% of the
produce in America

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:48.050
was grown in people's gardens.

00:19:48.050 --> 00:19:50.660
It was called a Victory Garden.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:52.370
And so, as Karen
mentioned, it just

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:57.050
seems insane to be growing
herbs and lettuces in the field

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:58.970
and then throwing it in
a clam-shell container

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.304
and shipping it across the
country when you could just

00:20:01.304 --> 00:20:02.720
be growing that
in the city and it

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:05.900
would be fresher and a way
to use food waste in places

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:07.640
that don't compost.

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:09.800
I think one thing that
we hadn't completely

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:14.330
understood before this project
was the ways in which soil

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:17.510
health interacted
with nutrition,

00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:20.660
and the ways in which there's
a lot of externalities

00:20:20.660 --> 00:20:22.250
in the food system,
and you're kind

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:25.890
of paying for government
subsidies and different things.

00:20:25.890 --> 00:20:29.120
This is just a little
snippet from a book that

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:31.370
shows some of the
nutrient differences

00:20:31.370 --> 00:20:34.850
between a USDA-approved
egg and a pastured egg

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:39.020
from a well-known farm
called Polyface in Virginia.

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:43.850
And some of the differences
are really surprising,

00:20:43.850 --> 00:20:46.670
and it's an orders of
magnitude difference

00:20:46.670 --> 00:20:48.800
in terms of nutrient intensity.

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:51.980
And the book goes on to kind
of mention that a USDA-approved

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:56.000
egg doesn't have anything to
do with growing practices,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.230
nutrition--

00:20:57.230 --> 00:20:58.260
literally anything.

00:20:58.260 --> 00:21:01.490
The only thing is the
size is the right size

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:03.344
and that it's not broken.

00:21:03.344 --> 00:21:05.510
So it could be covered with
salmonella or whatever--

00:21:05.510 --> 00:21:07.250
the USA doesn't care.

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:10.910
Meanwhile, Polyface Farms can't
even sell at a grocery store

00:21:10.910 --> 00:21:16.970
because it's not big enough
to qualify for the USDA stuff.

00:21:16.970 --> 00:21:18.770
So these are some
of the challenges

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:22.366
to small farmers and things
that, again, we don't really

00:21:22.366 --> 00:21:23.990
want to talk about
at the dinner table,

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:28.040
but lead to some of the
problems in the food system.

00:21:28.040 --> 00:21:31.200
And in a lot of
ways, climate change

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:37.020
is a good way to rally people
to support good farming.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:40.430
So then really quick,
also about nutrition,

00:21:40.430 --> 00:21:45.320
there's a prevailing notion
that the human body is absorbing

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:49.910
nutrients primarily driven
by how microbiology interacts

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:53.570
with and breaks down
food in the gut.

00:21:53.570 --> 00:21:57.470
And you can't just eat
a bunch of vitamins.

00:21:57.470 --> 00:21:59.109
You need to eat food
that has nutrients

00:21:59.109 --> 00:22:00.650
and then the
microbiology in your gut

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:03.020
kind of makes it
bioavailable to you.

00:22:03.020 --> 00:22:05.720
And then something
that also completely

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:09.395
surprised us, although
it makes perfect sense,

00:22:09.395 --> 00:22:11.240
is that plant
roots are basically

00:22:11.240 --> 00:22:16.610
like an inverted gut serving as
a home for all the microbiology

00:22:16.610 --> 00:22:18.740
that break down the
nutrients in the soil

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:20.600
and then provide
that to the plant

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:22.680
and make the plant healthy.

00:22:22.680 --> 00:22:26.400
So you can see there's some
little stats about how there

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:31.520
is significantly lower nutrient
density in a lot of food

00:22:31.520 --> 00:22:34.700
in the US as a result
of degraded soil.

00:22:34.700 --> 00:22:37.520
We're specifically
facing every day and sort

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:40.285
of dealing with consumers and
talking about these issues,

00:22:40.285 --> 00:22:41.660
but trying to find
a way to do it

00:22:41.660 --> 00:22:45.230
that takes two seconds
instead of 30 minutes

00:22:45.230 --> 00:22:47.900
because no one wants to hear
this talk at the dinner table

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:49.480
or anything like that.

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.950
And I feel like,
even for us, prior

00:22:51.950 --> 00:22:54.560
to getting into this project--

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:56.780
there's a picture here of
farmers market tomatoes,

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:58.550
organic tomatoes
at the supermarket,

00:22:58.550 --> 00:23:00.260
and conventional tomatoes.

00:23:00.260 --> 00:23:03.920
And it's sort of like, I
really had no idea what

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:05.150
the difference was.

00:23:05.150 --> 00:23:07.190
If someone asked me
to articulate it,

00:23:07.190 --> 00:23:09.410
I would have a hard
time articulating it.

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:13.712
And certified organic
can mean the farmer's

00:23:13.712 --> 00:23:15.170
doing really great
stuff, or it can

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:18.140
mean they're just not
using things that are not

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:20.060
approved on the approved list.

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:22.010
And so in a way
it's sort of like,

00:23:22.010 --> 00:23:24.080
there's actually
a whole lot more

00:23:24.080 --> 00:23:27.140
to farming that is
basically beyond organic,

00:23:27.140 --> 00:23:30.050
but how do we educate
people about this topic

00:23:30.050 --> 00:23:32.420
or even really understand it?

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:35.420
And so one thing that the
restaurant is embarking on

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:37.040
as kind of a project
in conjunction

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:40.010
with a lot of different
sustainable food organizations

00:23:40.010 --> 00:23:43.820
is making a little guide,
kind of the equivalent

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:47.720
of the Monterey Bay
Seafood Guide, maybe.

00:23:47.720 --> 00:23:51.950
And apparently there's a metric
that farmers measure called

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:55.370
soil organic matter, and it's
just part of the basic soil

00:23:55.370 --> 00:23:59.540
test, like pH, nitrogen,
and phosphorus levels,

00:23:59.540 --> 00:24:02.510
and then they just have a
percent soil organic matter.

00:24:02.510 --> 00:24:05.390
And so we're trying to work
with a lot of farmers and chefs

00:24:05.390 --> 00:24:09.560
to make this a bigger movement
to recognize healthy soil,

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:13.990
using that as a proxy for
a lot of good practices.

00:24:13.990 --> 00:24:16.430
And so it's a little bit
of an oversimplification

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:20.250
because it varies a little
bit from region to region.

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:22.555
You could also be
a great farmer who

00:24:22.555 --> 00:24:24.680
just took over degraded
land and you're bringing it

00:24:24.680 --> 00:24:26.220
up for different things.

00:24:26.220 --> 00:24:28.340
But in a lot of
ways, those are sort

00:24:28.340 --> 00:24:30.560
of the exceptions to the
rule and in a broader

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:34.730
way we're hoping that
this can kind of steer

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:37.490
the conversation in the
right direction of a focus

00:24:37.490 --> 00:24:38.430
towards healthy soil.

