or whatever, and really tried
not to impose the message.

00:28:54.720 --> 00:28:56.940
And other people come
in and they're like,

00:28:56.940 --> 00:28:58.710
I have seven questions.

00:28:58.710 --> 00:29:01.710
Should we do them
before I order or after?

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:04.290
They're really engaged.

00:29:04.290 --> 00:29:08.340
And so our goal is
to be kind of useful

00:29:08.340 --> 00:29:11.700
and move the conversation
for all of those people.

00:29:11.700 --> 00:29:15.360
And actually,
excitingly, lately we've

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:19.200
had an influx of
people who are going

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:22.050
to see Hamilton around the
corner from the restaurant.

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:25.544
And so they might not
have as much time,

00:29:25.544 --> 00:29:27.210
because they've got
to make the curtain,

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:31.410
but it's a whole range of
people who are not necessarily

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:34.530
coming for the
environmentalism, but it becomes

00:29:34.530 --> 00:29:36.380
part of the whole experience.

00:29:36.380 --> 00:29:42.816
It's a night out where all
kinds of synapses are firing.

00:29:42.816 --> 00:29:44.190
ANTHONY MYINT: I
think also we've

00:29:44.190 --> 00:29:49.540
started to gain a reputation
in the sustainable food

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:54.270
movement as a gathering place,
and so we have a lot of events.

00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:58.720
I was talking to people who were
working on a food waste dinner,

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:00.710
and we were talking, I
was making the rounds,

00:30:00.710 --> 00:30:02.540
and then they were
looking behind them

00:30:02.540 --> 00:30:04.790
and they were like, I think
that's our cricket farmer.

00:30:07.620 --> 00:30:10.770
It sort of feels a
little bit like the bar

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:13.970
across from City Hall where the
lawyers go and make the deals.

00:30:13.970 --> 00:30:16.410
And so it's kind of
fun to be part of that,

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:18.540
too, just in a physical way.

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:19.850
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah.

00:30:19.850 --> 00:30:21.570
Speaking of the bar,
I think that can

00:30:21.570 --> 00:30:25.720
be one way to engage with it.

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:28.260
The straws that we use
are not made from plastic.

00:30:28.260 --> 00:30:30.330
They're made from straw.

00:30:30.330 --> 00:30:32.310
And so people at first
are sort of like,

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:35.584
this is not what I'm used
to, and will really have

00:30:35.584 --> 00:30:36.750
a lot of questions about it.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:39.030
And the bartenders
are like, yeah,

00:30:39.030 --> 00:30:41.700
you can have seven of them if
you want because they're all

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:42.770
compostable.

00:30:42.770 --> 00:30:43.950
It's totally natural.

00:30:43.950 --> 00:30:47.100
And actually, plastic
straws are incredibly

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:48.550
wasteful in most bars.

00:30:48.550 --> 00:30:51.240
The bartenders use a couple
to stir and test and then

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:52.299
throw them away.

00:30:52.299 --> 00:30:53.340
And we have none of that.

00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:56.250
And so some of that stuff,
you just sort of like--

00:30:56.250 --> 00:30:59.412
it's like chatting with
the bartender, you know?

00:30:59.412 --> 00:31:00.120
SPEAKER: Awesome.

00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:05.850
So the salon for sustainability
is the hope, which I like that.

00:31:05.850 --> 00:31:08.531
A couple more
questions for you guys.

00:31:08.531 --> 00:31:10.530
I'm sure you're hoping
that the Perennial can be

00:31:10.530 --> 00:31:12.390
a model for other restaurants.

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:13.910
Do you know any
other restaurants

00:31:13.910 --> 00:31:16.130
that are doing similar work?

00:31:16.130 --> 00:31:18.990
How do you partner
with them if so?

00:31:18.990 --> 00:31:22.440
ANTHONY MYINT: Well, there
are two really great examples.

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:25.280
One is a restaurant in
upstate New York called

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:27.260
Blue Hill at Stone Barns.

00:31:27.260 --> 00:31:31.040
And the chef there probably
is, more than anyone,

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:35.120
responsible for kind of
spearheading what you

00:31:35.120 --> 00:31:37.250
might call farm-to-table 2.0.

00:31:37.250 --> 00:31:39.080
And he's working
with the breeders

00:31:39.080 --> 00:31:43.220
to basically breed heirloom
varieties of wheat,

00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:48.470
or breed a cross of squash that
is more flavorful, or whatever.

00:31:48.470 --> 00:31:53.160
So kind of doing more
than chopping, for sure.

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:54.920
And then the other
is a restaurant

00:31:54.920 --> 00:31:58.820
in Brighton in the
UK called Silo,

00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:00.710
and they're a
no-waste restaurant.

00:32:00.710 --> 00:32:01.300
Zero waste.

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:03.980
And so they have Big Bertha--

00:32:03.980 --> 00:32:06.710
their composter is
front and center.

00:32:06.710 --> 00:32:09.410
And they're growing mushrooms
from the coffee grounds.

00:32:09.410 --> 00:32:12.400
If the purveyors bring
produce in plastic bags,

00:32:12.400 --> 00:32:15.770
then there's a local artisan
who melts them down and makes

00:32:15.770 --> 00:32:17.720
plates with them,
and different stuff.

00:32:17.720 --> 00:32:21.200
And so we really admire
all these efforts

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:23.977
that everyone's doing.

00:32:23.977 --> 00:32:26.060
We happen to be located
in the middle of the city,

00:32:26.060 --> 00:32:28.440
so I think what
Dan Barber is doing

00:32:28.440 --> 00:32:30.470
at Blue Hill is
not available to us

00:32:30.470 --> 00:32:32.660
because they're
located on a farm.

00:32:32.660 --> 00:32:38.210
And then at Silo, I feel
like zero waste is amazing

00:32:38.210 --> 00:32:42.110
and we're trying to just
focus on climate change.

00:32:42.110 --> 00:32:44.300
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah, but
in terms of partnering,

00:32:44.300 --> 00:32:46.370
we definitely talk with
them and share ideas.

00:32:46.370 --> 00:32:49.910
And that is something
that's really fun

00:32:49.910 --> 00:32:52.640
that, when you have a
mission-driven business,

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.860
there's more of a
collaborative orientation.

00:32:54.860 --> 00:32:57.740
So we chat with the
folks from Silo.

00:32:57.740 --> 00:33:01.160
The people from Blue
Hill at Stone Barns

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:04.580
had a book party
with us last week.

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:07.604
There's sort of a sense
of a movement, which

00:33:07.604 --> 00:33:09.020
I think we're at
the beginning of,

00:33:09.020 --> 00:33:12.027
but it's exciting to kind
of make those connections.

00:33:12.027 --> 00:33:12.860
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:33:12.860 --> 00:33:14.818
Speaking of movements,
I know we're all looking

00:33:14.818 --> 00:33:17.000
for farm-to-table 2.0--

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:18.440
like, the new name.

00:33:18.440 --> 00:33:20.545
Because we might be over
that particular name.

00:33:20.545 --> 00:33:21.920
We might be saying
that too much.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:24.047
So if you've got a good
idea for us, let us know.

00:33:24.047 --> 00:33:25.422
I have one last
question and then

