00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.160
SPEAKER: Tell us more
about zero food print.

00:37:56.160 --> 00:37:57.520
ANTHONY MYINT: Sure.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:01.770
So zero food print actually
predated the Perennial.

00:38:01.770 --> 00:38:04.870
I was part of starting
that with a friend named

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:09.030
Chris Ying and an environmental
expert named Peter Fried.

00:38:09.030 --> 00:38:12.390
And Chris Ying used to be the
editor of Lucky Peach Magazine.

00:38:12.390 --> 00:38:14.940
And I think the
goal was basically

00:38:14.940 --> 00:38:20.800
to learn about how restaurants
are part of climate change.

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:23.730
And I think it started with
an initial question like,

00:38:23.730 --> 00:38:25.950
are restaurants really bad?

00:38:25.950 --> 00:38:28.560
How does it compare
to a home-cooked meal?

00:38:28.560 --> 00:38:30.330
So they did a
life-cycle analysis

00:38:30.330 --> 00:38:33.600
and kind of learned
that it's not that bad.

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:35.310
Pretty comparable to
a home-cooked meal

00:38:35.310 --> 00:38:36.600
for various reasons.

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:39.840
And then from there
sort of realized

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:43.260
that restaurants can
make small changes that

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:44.400
make a big difference.

00:38:44.400 --> 00:38:46.950
Most people are kind of too
focused on the day-to-day like,

00:38:46.950 --> 00:38:49.220
is my dishwasher going
to show up today?

00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:50.760
Or is my meat order
going to come?

00:38:50.760 --> 00:38:52.566
Or whatever.

00:38:52.566 --> 00:38:53.940
But then over the
course of it, I

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:57.870
think we learned a
lot of things like,

00:38:57.870 --> 00:38:59.730
the carbon footprint
of feed lot beef

00:38:59.730 --> 00:39:04.020
is so high that
serving fried chicken

00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:06.750
instead could be an
environmental act.

00:39:06.750 --> 00:39:09.510
Or just different ways
I think a lot of people

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:12.840
understand things like the
amount of calories in butter

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:14.880
versus celery, but
a lot of people

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:17.760
don't really understand the
carbon footprint of cheese

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:22.230
versus tomatoes is also
orders of magnitude different.

00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:24.110
And chefs and
restaurateurs, especially.

00:39:24.110 --> 00:39:26.514
So I think part of that was
to kind of educate chefs

00:39:26.514 --> 00:39:28.680
and restaurateurs, to let
them make the changes that

00:39:28.680 --> 00:39:30.510
were easy to make
and then give them

00:39:30.510 --> 00:39:33.430
a way to participate in a
food-related carbon offset

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:34.470
program.

00:39:34.470 --> 00:39:40.614
So a small share of a methane
digester on a dairy farm

00:39:40.614 --> 00:39:42.030
because a restaurant
is ultimately

00:39:42.030 --> 00:39:44.250
going to have some carbon
footprint because they're

00:39:44.250 --> 00:39:46.110
serving food and doing stuff.

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:50.580
But then they can kind of
facilitate positive work

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:52.560
somewhere else in
the food system.

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:55.770
And then basically qualify as
being zero food print or carbon

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:57.180
neutral.

00:39:57.180 --> 00:39:59.160
So in a lot of ways,
that's a top-down approach

00:39:59.160 --> 00:40:00.780
that any restaurant can adopt.

00:40:00.780 --> 00:40:02.280
KAREN LEIBOWITZ:
But just to clarify

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:05.340
that kind of relationship
among our projects--

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:07.710
we have the Perennial,
which is a restaurant that's

00:40:07.710 --> 00:40:11.380
really dedicated to the idea
that food can be regenerative,

00:40:11.380 --> 00:40:11.880
right?

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:15.150
So one of the terms that we use
instead of farm-to-table 2.0

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:17.160
is regenerative agriculture.

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:23.870
But we have the restaurant
that's sort of consumer-facing.

00:40:23.870 --> 00:40:25.530
And then we have
a nonprofit called

00:40:25.530 --> 00:40:29.250
Zero Food Print, which is
really chef-facing and saying,

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:33.330
here's how to assess
your footprint,

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:36.780
improve your footprint,
and offset your footprint.

00:40:36.780 --> 00:40:39.040
And then we have another
nonprofit as well,

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:42.750
which is farm-facing,
which is about sharing

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:46.416
information about soil
health, and best practices,

00:40:46.416 --> 00:40:47.290
and things like that.

00:40:47.290 --> 00:40:51.330
And so the whole
suite of activities

00:40:51.330 --> 00:40:54.390
is really about
saying, hey, there's

00:40:54.390 --> 00:40:56.580
only one thing that
we know right now that

00:40:56.580 --> 00:40:58.950
can draw down greenhouse gases.

00:40:58.950 --> 00:40:59.850
Let's get on that.

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:02.490
And so wherever
you are, wherever

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:07.902
you are within the food system,
here's how you can engage.

00:41:07.902 --> 00:41:09.360
SPEAKER: What kind
of adoption have

00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:13.370
you had with Zero Food Print?

00:41:13.370 --> 00:41:16.160
ANTHONY MYINT: So
this past year we

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:19.970
have started working with
about 20 restaurants.

00:41:19.970 --> 00:41:23.210
We would gladly welcome
any sort of larger

00:41:23.210 --> 00:41:25.175
institutional partnerships.

