At a larger
institutional level--

00:41:30.110 --> 00:41:33.850
Google, for example,
probably has a Director

00:41:33.850 --> 00:41:36.740
of Sustainability and they could
probably do their own research

00:41:36.740 --> 00:41:40.790
and find their own offsets
or buy a whole digester

00:41:40.790 --> 00:41:42.180
as their own program.

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:46.190
They wouldn't necessarily need
a slice of a pie of a project

00:41:46.190 --> 00:41:49.070
that someone else
is funding entirely,

00:41:49.070 --> 00:41:51.650
but we would love to work
with any organizations that

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:53.180
would want to work with us.

00:41:53.180 --> 00:41:54.096
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah.

00:41:54.096 --> 00:41:57.980
So Zero Food Print has
been expanding and working

00:41:57.980 --> 00:42:00.230
with restaurant groups,
which is interesting

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:03.740
because you can sort of compare
and contrast with a group.

00:42:03.740 --> 00:42:08.500
But we're really interested
also in getting into groceries

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:10.670
and thinking about
all the different ways

00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:13.350
that people access food.

00:42:13.350 --> 00:42:13.850
Yeah.

00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:17.330
And there is someone
who we've worked with,

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:20.360
kind of consulting on
food and carbon footprint

00:42:20.360 --> 00:42:24.830
data, this author who wrote
one of the books on the screen,

00:42:24.830 --> 00:42:26.580
"How Bad Are Bananas?"

00:42:26.580 --> 00:42:28.970
And it's basically like
the carbon footprint

00:42:28.970 --> 00:42:32.330
of a dozen eggs, or an
email, or your mortgage,

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:33.800
or driving across town.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:35.990
And he has done
a whole lifecycle

00:42:35.990 --> 00:42:39.980
analysis, or assessment,
for a UK groceries

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:41.540
chain called Tesco.

00:42:41.540 --> 00:42:44.930
And so one of their
stories is carbon neutral.

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:46.430
SPEAKER: Krista's
excellent question

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:48.270
was, where do we get
more of the good stuff?

00:42:48.270 --> 00:42:48.780
The Kernza.

00:42:48.780 --> 00:42:49.940
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:55.310
I think the Land Institute is
rapidly expanding production,

00:42:55.310 --> 00:42:58.790
but it is really
early days for Kernza.

00:42:58.790 --> 00:43:00.680
AUDIENCE: Is that
where yours comes from?

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:01.825
From Kansas or--

00:43:01.825 --> 00:43:03.200
ANTHONY MYINT: So
there's farmers

00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:07.370
growing Kernza in Illinois,
Kansas, and Minnesota.

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:09.590
Kind of like the
grain belt. And so it

00:43:09.590 --> 00:43:12.350
sort of wants winter
vernalization period

00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:14.780
to grow best, and since it's
kind of in the ramping-up up

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:17.570
stage it makes the most
sense to grow it in the place

00:43:17.570 --> 00:43:19.610
where it grows best.

00:43:19.610 --> 00:43:23.120
I should also say we don't
100% know all the answers

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:25.130
because they're
kind of changing,

00:43:25.130 --> 00:43:28.100
but our understanding
most recently

00:43:28.100 --> 00:43:33.680
is that the way that it
integrates with machinery

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:38.060
for processing and milling and
stuff, it is most like spelt.

00:43:38.060 --> 00:43:42.440
And they use a spelt dehuller,
but sometimes there's

00:43:42.440 --> 00:43:44.480
a little bit of hull left on it.

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:46.820
And so that is a
little bit labor

00:43:46.820 --> 00:43:50.090
intensive to get it perfect
for bread-making and stuff.

00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:55.160
So it's going to be commercially
available as flour in 2019,

00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:57.050
and it's available
as beer immediately

00:43:57.050 --> 00:43:59.570
because you can make
beer even if there's

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:01.160
a little bit of hull.

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:03.950
So that's a widespread
commercial project,

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:06.110
and they anticipate
based on kind

00:44:06.110 --> 00:44:08.060
of the arc of how the
natural breeding is

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:10.400
going, that they'll
be ready with flour

00:44:10.400 --> 00:44:11.790
in a couple of years.

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:14.600
And so it is pretty early,
but by the same token

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:18.580
a week or two ago General
Mills signed a deal with--

00:44:18.580 --> 00:44:20.910
or I don't know if that's
the right term, but is--

00:44:20.910 --> 00:44:21.310
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Committed.

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:22.143
ANTHONY MYINT: Yeah.

00:44:22.143 --> 00:44:23.660
Committed to
support the project.

00:44:23.660 --> 00:44:27.250
And so I don't know
the specifics of that,

00:44:27.250 --> 00:44:29.930
but I think it
involves guaranteeing

00:44:29.930 --> 00:44:31.910
farmers contracts to
start incorporating it

00:44:31.910 --> 00:44:35.019
into the Cascadian
Farms line or whatever,

00:44:35.019 --> 00:44:36.560
if that is of General
Mills, and then

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:40.790
also a $500,000 grant to
the University of Minnesota

00:44:40.790 --> 00:44:44.060
to continue research on it.

00:44:44.060 --> 00:44:49.400
So again, this is happening
now, or available now or soon,

00:44:49.400 --> 00:44:51.860
and then 10 or 20
years from now they

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:54.860
expect to also be
providing perennial wheat.

00:44:54.860 --> 00:44:57.790
And people in China are
working on perennial rice,

00:44:57.790 --> 00:45:00.530
and so I feel like
it's the very beginning

00:45:00.530 --> 00:45:07.500
of the shift of agriculture
back to natural systems.

00:45:07.500 --> 00:45:09.960
SPEAKER: I guess I would
sum that question up as,

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:11.750
tell us more about
what you are doing

00:45:11.750 --> 00:45:13.860
to get mainstream adoption.

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:17.420
And are you limited by things
like scale in the restaurant?

00:45:17.420 --> 00:45:20.050
ANTHONY MYINT: So we are working
with this ranch, Stemple Creek

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:21.890
Ranch, in part
because they are one

00:45:21.890 --> 00:45:24.980
of the pilot ranches with an
organization called the Marine

00:45:24.980 --> 00:45:26.560
Carbon Project.

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:30.110
And so we're really lucky to
have kind of stumbled onto it

00:45:30.110 --> 00:45:32.930
because they just are
an hour from here.

00:45:32.930 --> 00:45:36.560
And we visited the ranch,
and when we got there one

00:45:36.560 --> 00:45:40.370
of the founders was
sitting in a parking lot--

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:42.500
a windy parking lot
at the top of a hill--

00:45:42.500 --> 00:45:46.700
with a white board talking
to inspectors from the United

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:47.900
Nations.

00:45:47.900 --> 00:45:52.880
And kind of starting the
process of making carbon

00:45:52.880 --> 00:46:00.050
farming a recognized federal
subsidized type of activity.

00:46:00.050 --> 00:46:02.000
Like, measuring the
amount of carbon

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:04.070
and then starting
to divert money

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:05.840
to subsidize that
kind of farming.

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:09.080
And so there's actually many
different ranches in our area

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:11.720
that are working
on carbon ranching.

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:15.200
Tomcat Ranch and their
beef brand, which is called

00:46:15.200 --> 00:46:17.630
Left Coast Grass Fed.

00:46:17.630 --> 00:46:20.040
There's one called
Holistic Ag Beef.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:24.140
And [INAUDIBLE] Ranch
and True Grass Farm.

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:25.640
So there's a lot
of different people

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:28.640
who are independently
doing carbon farming.

00:46:28.640 --> 00:46:31.120
And there are people in
South Dakota, Montana,

00:46:31.120 --> 00:46:35.360
and all over the US who are kind
of doing it just because it's

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:37.040
a better yield anyway.

00:46:37.040 --> 00:46:39.264
So it just makes sense anyway.

00:46:39.264 --> 00:46:41.180
The breakthrough for the
Marine Carbon Project

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:44.542
is that they apply compost to
the field at the beginning,

00:46:44.542 --> 00:46:46.250
and that sort of
jump-starts the process.

00:46:46.250 --> 00:46:51.230
And also, contrary to what
scientists would expect,

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:54.020
actually leads to
durable soil carbon

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:57.140
that will last for
30 to 100 years,

00:46:57.140 --> 00:47:00.500
or continue to be sequestered
for 30 to 100 years

00:47:00.500 --> 00:47:05.330
just from one application and
then properly managed grazing.

00:47:05.330 --> 00:47:10.370
So in a lot of ways, that
is even more surprising

00:47:10.370 --> 00:47:14.600
how fast and optimistic
the message is.

00:47:14.600 --> 00:47:17.260
So the Marine Carbon Project
has three pilot branches now,

00:47:17.260 --> 00:47:20.900
and it's going to be 20
within a couple of years.

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:23.360
And their work is basically
to work with ranchers

00:47:23.360 --> 00:47:27.820
and create specific plans
for that ranch that's like,

00:47:27.820 --> 00:47:31.100
plant trees here, do this
for this part of the ranch,

00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:33.680
divert the pond here so
you can irrigate whatever.

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:37.280
And the whole thing
has a certain amount

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:40.310
of scientific rigor and
peer-reviewed carbon

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:44.000
sequestration assigned to
each action for each area.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:48.470
And then they can take that
carbon farm plan of like,

00:47:48.470 --> 00:47:52.100
we're going to sequester 10,000
tons over whatever time period

00:47:52.100 --> 00:47:55.790
to the government and
get money to start

00:47:55.790 --> 00:47:57.380
implementing that plan.

00:47:57.380 --> 00:47:59.310
So I think it will
be scaling up.

00:47:59.310 --> 00:48:01.160
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: And
you know, California

00:48:01.160 --> 00:48:10.360
has been working on how to apply
the carbon tax that we've had.

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:14.904
So there's the question of
how to reward people who

00:48:14.904 --> 00:48:16.070
are doing this kind of work.

00:48:16.070 --> 00:48:18.230
And so we've been a
little bit involved

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:25.940
in lobbying Sacramento for a
healthy soil initiative to say,

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:28.850
people in the city also care
about agricultural issues.

00:48:28.850 --> 00:48:32.360
So I think all in all, we
feel that it is very scalable.

00:48:32.360 --> 00:48:35.810
And we're sort of coming at it
from the direction of building

00:48:35.810 --> 00:48:40.267
consumer demand, talking
to the farmers that we know

00:48:40.267 --> 00:48:42.350
and connecting them with
resources like the Marine

00:48:42.350 --> 00:48:44.480
Carbon Project, and
then also working

00:48:44.480 --> 00:48:45.817
on it from a political angle.

00:48:45.817 --> 00:48:47.900
ANTHONY MYINT: But I think
also, if you think back

00:48:47.900 --> 00:48:53.300
to 10 years ago, I didn't
spend the extra dollars

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:56.677
on grass-fed beef, and
it wasn't as ubiquitous.

00:48:56.677 --> 00:48:58.760
And now it's kind of all
over the place and people

00:48:58.760 --> 00:49:01.370
are more used to spending
that extra dollar,

00:49:01.370 --> 00:49:04.151
and so in a lot of ways
we're just trying to--

00:49:04.151 --> 00:49:08.800
I hate to keep doing this, but
kind of kickstart grass-fed

00:49:08.800 --> 00:49:11.810
2.0 where it's like, cows are
part of the climate change

00:49:11.810 --> 00:49:15.500
solution, unless
they're feed-lot cows.

00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:17.200
Then that's part of the problem.

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:19.040
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Superbad.

00:49:19.040 --> 00:49:22.160
SPEAKER: So I think the
question is, grass-fed beef is

00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:23.480
more expensive.

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:26.060
Do you feel like the Bay
Area can sustain that?

00:49:26.060 --> 00:49:30.170
And if not, then are
other restaurants

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:32.600
going to be implementing
the true cost of food

00:49:32.600 --> 00:49:33.184
in the future?

00:49:33.184 --> 00:49:34.099
KAREN LEIBOWITZ: Yeah.

00:49:34.099 --> 00:49:36.320
I think your question
also is beyond the beef

00:49:36.320 --> 00:49:41.600
itself but just like,
is sustainable food

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:45.170
going to work as a
sustainable business model?

00:49:45.170 --> 00:49:49.100
And I think that is the
big experiment that we've

00:49:49.100 --> 00:49:53.720
embarked on, and the
Bay Area obviously

00:49:53.720 --> 00:49:57.170
is a kind of prime
place to try it out.

00:49:57.170 --> 00:49:59.390
I think the bigger
question is, could people

00:49:59.390 --> 00:50:03.740
do that outside of the Bay Area?

00:50:03.740 --> 00:50:06.020
But Anthony and I
were just talking

00:50:06.020 --> 00:50:10.820
this morning about kind of
that perception of value

00:50:10.820 --> 00:50:13.280
in food in America.

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:20.180
So I had read that in 1930,
the average American household

00:50:20.180 --> 00:50:22.880
spent 25% of its income on food.

00:50:22.880 --> 00:50:26.240
In 1950, that c was 30%.

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:27.470
It had gone up.

00:50:27.470 --> 00:50:29.070
And that it's now--

00:50:29.070 --> 00:50:31.430
in the thing I read it was
9% and Anthony was like,

00:50:31.430 --> 00:50:33.410
oh, I read 6.4%.

00:50:33.410 --> 00:50:36.770
So we now are spending just
a really small fraction

00:50:36.770 --> 00:50:40.640
of our income on food, and
it's much less actually

00:50:40.640 --> 00:50:43.340
than other comparable nations.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:46.250
And so we have ideas
about what food

00:50:46.250 --> 00:50:52.140
costs that are based on
pretty perverse incentives.

00:50:52.140 --> 00:50:57.710
So the way that our government
subsidizes poor agriculture

00:50:57.710 --> 00:51:00.980
has really set us up to
believe that food is cheap

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:02.450
and should always be cheap.

00:51:02.450 --> 00:51:05.810
And the ideas that we have
about how much meat costs,

00:51:05.810 --> 00:51:08.900
in particular, is really
based on something

00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:14.310
which is not really
defensible on any level--

00:51:14.310 --> 00:51:19.500
ethically or environmentally,
or even health.

00:51:19.500 --> 00:51:22.990
So I think that there
will be a big shift

00:51:22.990 --> 00:51:26.550
and the question is,
will people start

00:51:26.550 --> 00:51:30.720
seeing that fast enough for
us to survive as a business?

00:51:30.720 --> 00:51:34.560
Because our ideas about
these things change

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:39.150
kind of generationally, not in
the span of a restaurant lease.

00:51:39.150 --> 00:51:40.632
So we'll see.

